##Binary Search in C++

Binary Search is a fast and efficient searching algorithm used to find an element in a sorted array. Instead of checking every element one by one, it repeatedly divides the search space into two halves, making the search much quicker.

##How It Works

Start by checking the middle element of the array.
If the middle element matches the target, the search is complete.
If the target is smaller, continue searching in the left half.
If the target is larger, continue searching in the right half.
Repeat the process until the element is found or no elements remain to search.

##Features

Takes array elements as user input.
Searches for a given element using Binary Search.
Displays the position of the element if found.
Prints a message when the element is not present.

##Time Complexity

Best Case: O(1)
Average Case: O(log n)
Worst Case: O(log n)

##Note

Binary Search works only when the array is sorted. If the array is unsorted, the results will not be correct.


##code


#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int n, key;

    cout << "Enter the size of the array: ";
    cin >> n;

    int arr[n];

    cout << "Enter " << n << " elements in sorted order: ";
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        cin >> arr[i];
    }

    cout << "Enter the element to search: ";
    cin >> key;

    int low = 0, high = n - 1;

    while (low <= high)
    {
        int mid = (low + high) / 2;

        if (arr[mid] == key)
        {
            cout << "Element found at position " << mid + 1;
            return 0;
        }
        else if (arr[mid] < key)
        {
            low = mid + 1;
        }
        else
        {
            high = mid - 1;
        }
    }

    cout << "Element not found.";

    return 0;
}
